 a tree stump (see   Stock   3) or an occupational name for a tree cutter, from Middle High German <i>stocken</i> ‘to clear land’.","German and Swiss German (also <b>Stöcker</b>); Dutch: occupational name from Middle High German, Middle Dutch <i>stocker</i> ‘jailer’.","English: occupational name from Middle English <i>stokker</i> ‘one who sells stockfish’ (fish dried in the air without salt). This was the usual source of the name in medieval London, where a bylaw of 1419 stated that no <i>stokker</i> should board a ship to buy fish (presumably in order to forestall the market)."]}]},{"name":"Alice","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a variant of   Adelaide  , representing an Old French spelling of a reduced form of Germanic <i>Adalheidis</i>. <i>Alice</i> and <i>Adelaide</i> were already regarded as distinct names in English during the medieval period. <i>Alice</i> enjoyed a surge of popularity in the 19th century and periods of favour ever since. It was the name of the central character of  Lewis Carroll's  Alice's Adventures in Wonderland (  1865 ) and Through the Looking Glass (  1872 ), who was based on his child friend  Alice Liddell , daughter of the Dean of Christ Church, Oxford."],"variants":[{"name":"Alys","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Alice ."]},{"name":"Alis","meanings":["equivalent of <b>Alice</b> ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Alice Stafford was born about 1475. She had at least 1 son with Thomas Stafford."},"et":{"ABT    1475–":"umbes 1475–Surnud","1477–1517":"1477–1517","1475–Male":"1475–Surnud","1502–1532":"1502–1532","1505–Male":"1505–Surnud","1475–Female":"1475–Surnud","1502":"1502","ABT    1475":"umbes 1475","1532":"1532","1477":"1477","1475":"1475","ABT    1505":"umbes 1505","1517":"1517","1505":"1505","of Northants,England":"Northamptonshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"ABT    1475–":"noin 1475–Kuollut","1477–1517":"1477–1517","1475–Male":"1475–